  <section>
    <h2><span>#</span> My Work</h2>
    <p>
      In 2020 I joined
      <a href="https://thegraph.com/" rel="noreferrer">The Graph</a> as head
      protocol engineer to work on the largest blockchain indexing protocol. We
      built and launched the Graph Network <span>($GRT)</span>, and after a few
      years, I had the opportunity to lead the entire engineering team.
    </p>
    <p>
      In 2017, I became a founding engineer at
      <a href="https://decentraland.org" rel="noreferrer">Decentraland</a>
      <span>($MANA)</span>, where I led a team developing the first
      community-owned Metaverse. Our team pioneered a vast virtual world with an
      <a
        href="https://decentraland.org/blog/platform/designing-genesis-city-roads-urban-planning/"
        rel="noreferrer"
        >in-game economy</a
      >, empowering players with
      <a href="/introducing-the-decentraland-marketplace" rel="noreferrer"
        >ownership of digital assets</a
      >.
    </p>
    <p>
      Before that, in 2016, I served as
      <a href="/two-years-into-the-crypto-rabbit-hole" rel="noreferrer"
        >CTO of PopChest</a
      >, where we built a video streaming platform that allowed fans to directly
      pay content creators without intermediaries. That project led me to San
      Mateo, California, where I joined
      <a
        href="https://medium.com/boost-vc/say-hello-to-tribe-8-a28bab4fe0bd"
        rel="noreferrer"
        >Tribe 8</a
      >
      of <a href="https://www.boost.vc" rel="noreferrer">Boost VC</a> incubator.
    </p>
    <p>
      In 2010, I founded Oony, a shopping guide with automated recommendations
      based on users’ preferences, which grew to over 3 million products across
      15 countries. The project was originally launched as Weegoh in 2008, the
      first location-based social network for mobile devices in Latin America,
      before pivoting to become Oony.
    </p>
  </section>
